{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NWe9MWEsJj6mmpZ7YtWStj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly**\n- MOCK-MISS: This is testing one function's logic — the SUM function evaluation. It's testing the formula parser + evaluator for a range reference. This could be tested at Unit level.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No external dependencies to mock.\n- LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No multiple agentic steps.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: Unit — this is testing the formula evaluation logic for a single built-in function with range references. \n\nIt's a pure algorithmic test.\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula references**\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests whether formulas can resolve references across cells — when B1 contains a formula and C1 references B1, the cascading dependency resolution needs to work. This could be Unit if the cell graph is self-contained, or Integration if the parser, evaluator, and reference resolver are separate modules working together.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network involved.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThe core question is whether the failure only surfaces when modules hand off data to each other. If the formula evaluator has its own cell lookup mechanism, it might be Unit. But typically the evaluator calls into a separate cell store, which crosses a module boundary. I'm leaning toward Integration since the cascaded evaluation requires the formula evaluator and cell reference resolver to interact.\n\nFor circular dependency detection, it's a pure algorithmic test on the dependency graph—likely Unit. Though the implementation matters; if it's tightly coupled with the cell storage and evaluator, it could be Integration.\n\nFor VLOOKUP exact match, that's straightforward Unit testing—just feed the function a table and key to verify correctness.\n\nNow looking at IF with nested conditions...\n\nthat's also pure formula evaluation logic, testable at the Unit level.\n\nCONCATENATE's behavior with empty cells is another Unit test—I'm verifying the function skips empties rather than inserting blanks.\n\nCross-sheet formula references are trickier since they involve the parser and the sheet lookup module working together, so I need to see where that interaction breaks down.\n\nDependency recalculation in topological order is definitely Integration-level—it requires the dependency tracker, recalculation scheduler, and evaluator all coordinating to ensure cells update in the right sequence.\n\nUndo operations are similarly Integration-level since they need the history stack, cell store, formula evaluator, and dependency tracker working together to restore both the formula text and all dependent values. Save and load operations test the full serialization pipeline against actual file I/O.\n\nFor the save/load behavior, the real failure mode is in the custom binary format's encoding and decoding logic, particularly around floating-point precision preservation. An in-memory buffer would catch most serialization bugs without needing actual disk I/O, so this is also Integration-level.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the earlier behaviors with the same lens. For the SUM function, circular dependencies, and the other cases, none of them require real OS/network operations, AI/ML outputs, or chained agentic steps—they're all Unit-level tests.\n\nLet me finalize the classification: SUM and circular dependency detection are Unit, VLOOKUP and nested IF conditions are Unit, CONCATENATE with empty cells is Unit. The Integration tests cover cascaded formula references, cross-sheet references, topological recalculation, undo/redo with dependents, and the save/load roundtrip.\n\nSince I don't have a prior plan to compare against, I'll mark everything as plan-consistent with no additional notes needed.\n\nNow I'm working through the detailed analysis for each behavior, starting with SUM which tests the formula evaluator's range aggregation logic in isolation with an in-memory cell grid, then moving to cascaded formula references which requires Integration testing since it involves cross-cell dependencies and module boundaries.\n\nFor circular dependency detection, I'm considering that cycle detection is fundamentally a graph algorithm problem that can be tested at the Unit level by feeding circular references directly to the dependency checker without needing the full system.\n\nFor VLOOKUP, I'm recognizing this as a pure function test where I can verify both successful lookups and error cases by setting up an in-memory table and testing against known keys.\n\nMoving to nested IF conditions, these are straightforward AST evaluation problems—I can test all the conditional branches by varying a single cell value and checking that the formula selects the right path each time.\n\nNow I'm looking at CONCATENATE behavior with empty cells...\n\nthe function needs to skip over blanks rather than including them as empty strings, which is purely internal logic testable with an in-memory cell array. For cross-sheet references, though, the formula evaluator has to actually communicate with the workbook manager to find and resolve cells on other sheets, so that bumps up to integration testing.\n\nNow I'm looking at topological recalculation order—this is where the dependency graph, scheduler, and evaluator all have to coordinate properly. A single mocked component would hide the real ordering issues, so this definitely requires integration testing to catch failures in how these pieces work together.\n\nFor the undo behavior, I need to verify that restoring a formula also restores all its dependent values correctly. This involves the history stack, cell storage, formula text, and the recalculator all synchronizing—another integration-level concern where mocking any one piece would mask the real bugs in how they coordinate.\n\nFor the save/load roundtrip, I'm checking that serializing and deserializing a workbook preserves everything exactly. The custom binary format is where floating-point precision issues hide, and using an in-memory buffer lets me test the codec without filesystem complications. I'll populate cells with various types including floats, round-trip through serialization, and verify all values and formulas match precisely.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering behavior 3 on circular dependencies. The key question is whether the failure only surfaces when the formula parser actually feeds into the dependency builder, or if detecting the cycle itself is the core behavior. The behavior text specifically says \"detects a circular dependency and returns an error,\" so I need to think about what level of integration is actually required to exercise that detection logic.\n\nA unit test could build the dependency graph directly and verify the cycle detection algorithm works in isolation. The disqualifying factor for Integration would be if the behavior is purely algorithmic — but returning the error might still benefit from integration testing to ensure the full flow works. I'm settling on Unit at 0.65 and Integration at 0.30 for behavior 3.\n\nNow I'm finalizing the probability distributions across all behaviors to make sure each sums to 1.0. I'm verifying that all the test cases have probability distributions that sum to 1.0, which they do.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10334,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10334},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e4d788fc-b94c-4978-8c56-2dbc673a1d9e","uuid":"617c4134-dc64-47ee-8b15-5fe7cb562834"}
